sinz 2025-03-04 05:22 p.m.
While I acknowledge that common law principles generally require at least two individuals for a conspiracy charge, I'd add that usually conspiracy charges would explicitly state two or more people in the statutory language, see 18 U.S. Code 371. However, the statutory language of 1 M.S.C. 4201 states that any player who plans, or participates in a plan to commit a crime, and then carries out one action towards completing the plan shall be guilty of a felony.

The statute includes plans as an independent basis for culpability, which may indicate the legislative intent to criminalize an individuals unilateral preparation if followed by an overt act. However, if the court determines that the common law requirement of two or more persons is controlling even when the language of the law would suggest otherwise, the court should deduce that Jane Doe is the co-conspirator.

"A common law conspiracy consists of two or more persons combined to accomplish, by some concerted action, some criminal or unlawful purpose or some lawful purpose by a criminal or unlawful means," Commercial Bus. Sys., Inc. v. BellSouth Svcs., Inc., 249 Va. 39, 48, 453 S.E.2d 261 (1995) (citing Hechler Chevrolet v. General Motors Corp., 230 Va. 396, 402, 337 S.E.2d 744 (1985))

A combination or confederacy between two or more persons formed for the purpose of committing, by their joint efforts, some unlawful or criminal act, or some act which is innocent in itself, but becomes unlawful when done by the concerted action of the conspirators, or for the purpose of using criminal or unlawful means to the commission of an act not in itself unlawful.

sinz 2025-03-04 05:46 p.m.
Your Honor, I respectfully submit that the case law citedCommercial Business Systems, Inc. v. BellSouth Services, Inc.concerns civil conspiracy, which operates under a different standard than criminal conspiracy. Civil conspiracy typically pertains to a tort-based cause of action requiring a combination of two or more individuals to harm another party, while criminal conspiracy is an offense against the state.

Furthermore, criminal conspiracy statutes often derive their elements from statutory law rather than common law, and while common law principles inform statutory interpretation, they do not override explicit legislative intent. 1 M.S.C. 4201 criminalizes an individual who plans, or participates in a plan and then commits an overt act toward the crime. The inclusion of plans as a standalone basis for liability suggests that an individual actor may be culpable if they take steps toward executing their own criminal plan.

I respectfully request that the court consider controlling criminal precedent addressing the elements of conspiracy rather than civil case law, which operates under a different legal framework.

sinz 2025-03-04 06:38 p.m.
The legislature has the power to define crimes and establish their elements. When a statute defines an offense, courts are bound to apply it as written unless unconstitutional. If a statute modifies or departs from common law (although civil caselaw interpreting civil conspiracy does not apply here), the statute governs.

Courts do not apply civil definitions to criminal cases, just as civil conspiracy principles should not dictate the interpretation of a criminal conspiracy statute.

1 M.S.C. 4201 clearly defines the offense within the statutory framework, and its elements should be interpreted as written. Courts cannot import common law principlesespecially from the civil contextto impose additional requirements not found in the statutory text.

@Charles Before we proceed, I must ensure you understand your rights in this matter:

1. You have the right to remain silent. This means you do not have to speak or provide any information that could incriminate you.

2. You also have the right to have an attorney present during any questioning or legal proceedings. If you cannot afford an attorney, one will be appointed for you at no cost.

3. You have the right to a fair and public trial, where evidence will be presented, and witnesses can be called to testify on your behalf.

4. Furthermore, you have the right to confront witnesses against you, meaning you can question them in court.

5. Finally, you have the right to appeal any conviction or sentence imposed upon you.

This is Case Number CR-0073-25 before the Mayflower District Court in the County of Clark: State of Mayflower v. VuIkanwerft. The information is as follows:

COUNT 1: UNLICENSED POSSESSION OF A FIREARM (1 M.S.C. 6102)
On or about March 3, 2025, Defendant VuIkanwerft did possess a non-civil grade
firearm, to wit, an Upgraded XR21, restricted to national guardsmen, without
holding a state-issued firearms license and not being a state-certified peace officer
or authorized national guardsman, in violation of 1 M.S.C. 6102.

COUNT 2: CONSPIRACY TO COMMIT A CRIME (1 M.S.C. 4201)
On or about March 3, 2025, Defendant VuIkanwerft did plan or participate in a
plan to commit a crime, to wit, the illegal sale of a firearm, and carried out an
action toward completing the plan by displaying an Upgraded XR21 to coconspirator Jane Doe to confirm its existence for payment, in violation of 1 M.S.C.
4201.

Signed March 3, 2025, by State Attorney JustTheJudge1.
